In this proclamation, President Barack Obama declares November 2014 as National Alzheimer's Disease Awareness Month. He highlights that as many as 5 million Americans live with Alzheimer's disease, a progressive and fatal illness that affects memory, behavior, and independence. The President emphasizes the government's commitment to finding ways to prevent and effectively treat Alzheimer's by 2025. He mentions the National Plan to Address Alzheimer's Disease and the efforts to enhance care, expand support, and strengthen partnerships in the Alzheimer's community. The President also mentions funding for clinical trials, training for healthcare providers, and investments in research through the BRAIN Initiative. He encourages Americans to visit www.Alzheimers.gov for more information and resources. The proclamation recognizes those who have lost their lives to Alzheimer's and honors the dedication of caregivers. Finally, President Obama calls upon the people of the United States to learn more about Alzheimer's disease and support individuals living with the disease and their caregivers.